    detail: "Compression profiles are named parameter sets — the embedded recipes (claude-code, codex-safe, codex-variant) plus `default` (your master compression settings) — resolved per request at the proxy boundary.\n\n• Default profile — what traffic without a per-provider assignment runs.\n• Anthropic traffic — requests on the Anthropic Messages API path (Claude Code). Tuned default: claude-code, the cache-aware parameter set measured NOT to break Anthropic prompt caching.\n• OpenAI traffic — requests on the OpenAI paths (codex). Tuned default: codex-safe (logs-only). Running a *-codex reasoning model? Assign codex-variant — any per-type compression measurably degrades those models.\n\nThe master Compression → Conversation `enabled` switch stays the ONLY on/off gate: profiles supply parameters once compression is on and never enable it themselves.\n\nSaves apply to NEW sessions immediately (no restart): the daemon re-points its profile router on every config save. Sessions already in flight keep the parameters they started with — deliberate, because mid-session parameter flips would corrupt rolling-summary state and break cache alignment. A session sticks to its profile for its lifetime.\n\nCLI parity: `observer profile list | show <name> | assign <class> <profile>`. The wrong pairing can break provider caching or degrade output — when in doubt, keep the defaults.",
