    detail: "The Set up button on a Connected-tools row opens the per-tool wizard. Three steps, each independent:\n\n• Hooks — registers observer's turn-boundary hooks into the tool's own config file. The no-proxy capture path.\n• MCP server — registers the observer MCP server (13 on-demand project-knowledge tools) into the tool's config. The step states the honest trade-off: the tool schemas add roughly 1,800 tokens to every turn. It is never pre-selected — skip it and everything else still works.\n• Proxy route — the durable routing write (Claude Code / codex only), same preview-confirm-409-force contract as the Compression page buttons.\n\nConsent model: every step shows a dry-run PREVIEW of the exact file change first, and nothing is written until you click that step's own button. There is no \"apply all\". Conflicts (an entry pointing somewhere you configured deliberately) are refused with an explanation; a separate Force overwrite click is required to replace them.\n\ncodex extra: after registering hooks, codex requires you to TRUST each hook event inside codex itself before it runs. The wizard's Hook-trust card reads that state and shows the exact instruction — observer can never set trust for you (deliberately: it is codex's own security boundary).\n\nServer-side, the wizard drives the same registries as `observer init` — the written bytes are identical, and re-running either is idempotent.\n\nUndoing: every write the wizard makes is reversible. `observer uninstall --<tool>` removes ONLY observer's own entries (hooks, MCP server, proxy route) from that tool's config — user-authored hooks and other MCP servers in the same file are preserved. Scope the removal with `--skip-hooks` / `--skip-mcp`, preview with `--dry-run`. Safety: uninstall compares each file against the checksum recorded at write time and refuses a file something else has modified since (override with `--force` once you've checked why). `--purge` additionally deletes ~/.observer/ (database, config, checksums) for a full clean exit. Hand-removal also works — each step's result line names the exact file, and the routing buttons state their own one-line undo.",
